David Saff wrote:

&gt; J. B. Rainsberger wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt; Elliotte Harold wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; Or perhaps what we need is some nice Eclipse refactorings that 
&gt; move test
&gt; &gt; &gt; methods into new classes.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Extract Class! Absolutely we need it.
&gt;
&gt; Extract Class would be cool to have.  As a general refactoring, it&#39;s not
&gt; quite the same thing as what we want for JUnit tests, however.  What we
&gt; want is for Eclipse to understand test fixtures, test methods, and
&gt; setUp.  For example, if we extract SecondTest from FirstTest, and they
&gt; share no fixtures, neither need reference the other at all.  For general
&gt; Java classes, you&#39;d want to Extract Superclass and then Replace
&gt; Inheritance with Delegation (neither of which Eclipse really has,
&gt; unfortunately).  The refactoring I&#39;ve wanted most is Replace Query with
&gt; Fixture.  For example, from:
&gt;
&gt; public void testA() {
&gt;     Component comp = new Component(5);
&gt;     assertEquals(6, comp.successor());
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; public void testB() {
&gt;     Component comp = new Component(5);
&gt;     assertEquals(4, comp.predecessor());
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; I can automatically Extract Method to get:
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; public void testA() {
&gt;     Component comp = theComponent();
&gt;     assertEquals(6, comp.successor());
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; public void testB() {
&gt;     Component comp = theComponent();
&gt;     assertEquals(4, comp.predecessor());
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; private Component theComponent() {
&gt;     return new Component(5);
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; But I want the next step automatically, as well:
&gt;
&gt; public void setUp() {
&gt;     Component fComp = new Component(5);
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; public void testA() {
&gt;     assertEquals(6, fComp.successor());
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; public void testB() {
&gt;     assertEquals(4, fComp.predecessor());
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Anyone else had this desire?
